                            <votes>0</votes>
                                    <watches>0</watches>
                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13414" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 1 Jun 2005 00:44:06 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Indeed, we shouldn&apos;t rely on a a thread context class loader there. I&apos;ve added a further check to use the class loader that ClassPathResource has been loaded with as fallback.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However, it is usually preferable to pass in a ClassLoader explicitly in such a scenario, through the corresponding ClassPathResource constructor.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13420" author="michiel" created="Wed, 1 Jun 2005 07:22:07 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Yes, I agree it is preferable to pass in a ClassLoader explicitly. However, in the specific case I have the problem this is not possible because the ClassPathResource is constructed within the JDBC package of Spring itself. It is used to find the SQL error messages (org/springframework/jdbc/support/sql-error-codes.xml). So, thanks for fixing it!&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
